bug.short_desc: Installation fails with "AttributeError: module 'blivet.arch' has no attribute 'get_arch'
bug.cf_doc_type: If docs needed, set a value

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1172039 syslog
Description of problem: Since Fedora 24 GA, I am getting the following installation error while attempting to install my Fedora spin using text install via kickstart (spin created using pungi):
anaconda 24.13.7-1 for Test 24 started. * installation log files are stored in /tmp during installation * shell is available on TTY2 * when reporting a bug add logs from /tmp as separate text/plain attachments 20:53:07 Running pre-installation scripts Traceback (most recent call last): File "/sbin/anaconda", line 934, in <module> ksdata = kickstart.parseKickstart(ks) File "/usr/lib64/python3.5/site-packages/pyanaconda/kickstart.py", line 2120, in parseKickstart handler = AnacondaKSHandler(addon_paths["ks"]) File "/usr/lib64/python3.5/site-packages/pyanaconda/kickstart.py", line 2046, in __init__ File "/usr/share/anaconda/addons/com_redhat_kdump/ks/kdump.py", line 42, in __init__ File "/usr/share/anaconda/addons/com_redhat_kdump/common.py", line 65, in getMemoryBounds if blivet.arch.get_arch() == 'ppc64': AttributeError: module 'blivet.arch' has no attribute 'get_arch'
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): kexec-tools-anaconda-addon-2.0.12-5.fc24.x86_64
How reproducible: Always
Steps to Reproduce: 1. Build my spin using pungi. 2. Install the resulting ISO to a VM.
Actual results: The traceback above and "Pane is dead" at the bottom of the screen.
Expected results: Installation proceeds as normal.
Additional info: I did a diff of the files provided by version 2.0.12-2 and 2.0.12-5 and the method call was changed from blivet.arch.getArch to blivet.arch.get_arch, but I don't know what else needs to be updated to sync up with these changes.
Created attachment 1172040 anaconda.log
Created attachment 1172041 program.log
Created attachment 1172042 storage.log

Can I please get some sort of response about this? This is literally a showstopper for my development. Since the kexec code is apparently embedded in the installer, I cannot create an installable ISO via pungi when downloading using the Fedora 24 repositories.
I believe this issue was clearly created by an update in kexec-tools-anaconda-addon-2.0.12-5.fc24.x86_64, as noted by this changlog entry:
* Tue Mar 29 2016 Dave Young <dyoung@redhat.com> - 2.0.12-3 - update kdump anaconda addon to adapt to blivet-2.0 API
I suspect this is where blivet.arch.getArch() became blivet.arch.get_arch().
Installations based on 2.0.12-2 were working flawlessly. But, after the update to 2.0.12-5, things broke as described in the traceback.
If there is a workaround, I will be happy to try it.
Add David Lehman in cc, is this wrong in F24?
Roger, does inst.kdump_addon=off in kernel cmdline works?

(In reply to Dave Young from comment #5) > Add David Lehman in cc, is this wrong in F24?
blivet-2.x is not in F24. It will be in F25.

I booted the VM while pointing the CD to my ISO, hit the tab key to get to the boot command line and added "inst.kdump_addon=off" to the end of the line. I see the same failure/traceback. On the TTY2 console, I see the following:
[anaconda root@localhost /] cat /proc/cmdline BOOT_IMAGE=vmlinuz initrd=initrd.img inst.ks=hd:LABEL=Test:/ks-test.cfg inst.stage2=hd:LABEL=Test quiet inst.kdump_addon=off

(In reply to David Lehman from comment #7) > (In reply to Dave Young from comment #5) > > Add David Lehman in cc, is this wrong in F24? > > blivet-2.x is not in F24. It will be in F25.
Hmm, It should a mistake. Seems no way to fix it since it is already in the iso?
Roger, can you try install with extra cmdline param like below? updates=http://people.redhat.com/ruyang/f24-updates.img
If it works you can also put it on any web server and use it in updates= cmdline.
Thanks Dave
BTW, does it happen on all installation method? GUI/text/kickstart..

I tried the installation (without updates=...) with the GUI & text install types and both failed in the same way as described in the original post.
BTW, we have a winner! :-) Adding the updates=http://... cmdline parameter does the trick. My installation proceeds as expected. Well done!
So, is this image something I can pull into my ISO build so that it is included and I don't have to add the updates= cmdline parameter? I guess what I am looking for is a way to integrate this so that I don't require network access for installation.

Oh, I also wanted to mention that I tried my build on Rawhide and the ISO that is produced does not exhibit the blivet failure (I have other issues, primarily unsatisfied library dependencies, but that's a completely different thing).

My excitement may have been a bit premature, or perhaps I don't fully understand how all this stuff works (which is far more likely the case). Adding the updates=http://... cmdline parameter does indeed eliminate the traceback/failure that I posted originally, however the installation proceeds to install what appears to be the minimal set of Fedora 24 packages (269 packages, to be exact). I am expecting to install over 800 packages based on the contents of my kickstart file and the dependencies I call out in the custom packages that I build for inclusion in my ISO. So, am I missing something here?

Roger,
The updates is based below branch: https://github.com/daveyoung/kdump-anaconda-addon/tree/f24-revert-blivet-update
The only thing is revert the getarch callback, a one line change.
Updates.img contains only kdump addon which overwrites the addon in iso. The problem you mentioned in comment#13 should be other problem.
I'm not sure how to pack the updates into an iso, for testing purpose I use this scripts which is ugly: https://github.com/daveyoung/kdump-anaconda-addon/blob/f24-revert-blivet-update/test/packbootiso.sh
Thanks Dave

Thanks Dave. The script that you pointed to is exactly what I need to integrate your fix. My question is, if you submit this fix, will the installer bits get updated so that when I use a utility like 'pungi' to build my ISO, your fix will be included, or will I need to build my own version of install.img that contains the fix?
kexec-tools-2.0.12-7.fc24.1 has been submitted as an update to Fedora 24. https://bodhi.fedoraproject.org/updates/FEDORA-2016-cbd97b6ce9

Roger, I'm not sure because I do not know the compose build process. but I think if pungi can pull the build below, it should contain the fix: http://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji/buildinfo?buildID=777567
updates.img is for using in cmdline option updates=, you can create it by yourself. * clone the kdump addon git tree * checkout f24-revert-blivet-update branch * cd test; ./makeimage
